icture/cover/1333460418.gif',NULL),(2009110,'Enhanced toluene sensing characteristics of TiO2-doped flowerlike ZnO nanostructures','<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"abstract svAbstract\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-size: 13px; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: -2px; margin-left: 0px; padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(46, 46, 46); font-family: \'Arial Unicode MS\', \'Arial Unicode\', Arial, \'URW Gothic L\', Helvetica, Tahoma, sans-serif; line-height: 20px; \">\r\n	<p id=\"\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 9px; margin-left: 0px; padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; word-spacing: -0.15ex; text-align: justify; \">\r\n		The large-scale flowerlike ZnO nanostructures, consisting of many aggregative nanorods with the diameter of about 60&nbsp;nm, were prepared by a simple and facile hydrothermal route. The toluene sensing properties of the pure ZnO and TiO<sub style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-size: 0.75em; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; line-height: 0; \">2</sub>-doped ZnO nanostructures were tested at different operating temperatures from 160 to 390&nbsp;&deg;C and toluene concentrations ranging from 1 to 3000&nbsp;ppm. The results indicate that the response of the ZnO nanostructures towards toluene was enhanced significantly by TiO<sub style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-size: 0.75em; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; line-height: 0; \">2</sub>&nbsp;doping, which was deposited onto the ZnO products by evaporation. It is found that the TiO<sub style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-size: 0.75em; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; line-height: 0; \">2</sub>-doped ZnO sensor exhibits remarkably enhanced response of 17.1 at the optimal operating temperature of 290&nbsp;&deg;C to 100&nbsp;ppm toluene, which has been improved up from 7.4 at 390&nbsp;&deg;C from pure ZnO nanostructures.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"sgfNoTitleBar sgfNoGadgetBorder svDoNotLink ui-sortable\" id=\"SD_BA1P\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-size: 13px; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px; padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(46, 46, 46); font-family: \'Arial Unicode MS\', \'Arial Unicode\', Arial, \'URW Gothic L\', Helvetica, Tahoma, sans-serif; line-height: 20px; \">\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<h2 id=\"kwd_N2120ea60N4de70980\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: 10